"Hansen J., Ruedy R., Sato M., Imhoff M., Lawrence W., Easterling D., Peterson T., Karl T.","A closer look at United States and global surface temperature change",2001,"Journal of Geophysical Research Atmospheres","106","D20", 2001JD000354,"23947","23963",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0035193861&partnerID=40&md5=64fbb4241dd351ca04b286b4d1662c80","NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States; NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Greenbelt, MD, United States; NOAA National Climatic Data Center, Asheville, NC, United States; NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Greenbelt, MD 20771, United States; NOAA National Climatic Data Center, Asheville, NC 28801, United States","Hansen, J., NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States, NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; Ruedy, R., NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States, NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; Sato, M., NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States, NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; Imhoff, M., NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Greenbelt, MD, United States, NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Greenbelt, MD 20771, United States; Lawrence, W., NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Greenbelt, MD, United States, NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Greenbelt, MD 20771, United States; Easterling, D., NOAA National Climatic Data Center, Asheville, NC, United States, NOAA National Climatic Data Center, Asheville, NC 28801, United States; Peterson, T., NOAA National Climatic Data Center, Asheville, NC, United States, NOAA National Climatic Data Center, Asheville, NC 28801, United States; Karl, T., NOAA National Climatic Data Center, Asheville, NC, United States, NOAA National Climatic Data Center, Asheville, NC 28801, United States","We compare the United States and global surface air temperature changes of the past century using the current Goddard Institute for Space Studies (GISS) analysis and the U.S. Historical Climatology Network (USHCN) record [Karl et al., 1990]. Changes in the GISS analysis subsequent to the documentation by Hansen et al. [1999] are as follows: (1) incorporation of corrections for time-of-observation bias and station history adjustments in the United States based on Easterling et al. [1996a], (2) reclassification of rural, small-town, and urban stations in the United States, southern Canada, and northern Mexico based on satellite measurements of night light intensity [Imhoff et al., 1997], and (3) a more flexible urban adjustment than that employed by Hansen et al. [1999], including reliance on only unlit stations in the United States and rural stations in the rest of the world for determining long-term trends. We find evidence cf local human effects (""urban warming"") even in suburban and small-town surface air temperature records, but the effect is modest in magnitude and conceivably could be an artifact of inhomogeneities in the station records. We suggest further studies, including more complete satellite night light analyses, which may clarify the potential urban effect. There are inherent uncertainties in the long-term temperature change at least of the order of 0.1°C for both the U.S. mean and the global mean. Nevertheless, it is clear that the post-1930s cooling was much larger in the United States than in the global mean. The U.S. mean temperature has now reached a level comparable to that of the 1930s, while the global temperature is now far above the levels earlier in the century. The successive periods of global warming (1900-1940), cooling (1940-1965), and warming (1965-2000) in the 20th century show distinctive patterns of temperature change suggestive of roles for both climate forcings and dynamical variability. The U.S. was warm in 2000 but cooler than the warmest years in the 1930s and 1990s. Global temperature was moderately high in 2000 despite a lingering La Niña in the Pacific Ocean. Copyright 2001 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"air temperature; nightglow; satellite data; surface temperature; temperature anomaly; United States",,,,,,"Delworth, T.L., Knutson, T.R., Simulation of early 20th century global warming (2000) Science, 287, pp. 2246-2250; Easterling, D.R., Peterson, T.C., A new method for detecting undocumented discontinuities in climatological time series (1995) Int. J. Climatol., 15, pp. 369-377; Easterling, D.R., Karl, T.R., Mason, E.H., Hughes, P.Y., Bowman, D.P., Daniels, R.C., Boden, T.A., (1996) United States Historical Climatology Network (USHCN), Environ. Sci. Div. Publ. 4500, , Carbon Dioxide Inf. and Anal. Cent., Oak Ridge Natl. Lab, Oak Ridge, Tenn; Easterling, D.R., Peterson, T.C., Karl, T.R., On the development and use of homogenized climate data sets (1996) J. Clim., 9, pp. 1429-1434; Easterling, D.R., Maximum and minimum temperature trends for the globe (1997) Science, 277, pp. 364-367; Folland, C.K., Sexton, D.M.H., Karoly, D.J., Johnson, C.E., Rowell, D.P., Parker, D.E., Influences of anthropogenic and oceanic forcing on recent climate change (1998) Geophys. Res. Lett., 25, pp. 353-356; Hansen, J., Forcings and chaos in interannual to decadal climate change (1997) J. Geophys. Res., 102, pp. 25,679-25,720; Hansen, J., Sato, M., Lacis, A., Ruedy, R., Tegen, I., Matthews, E., Climate forcings in the industrial era (1998) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci., 95, pp. 12,753-12,758; Hansen, J., Ruedy, R., Glascoe, J., Sato, M., GISS analysis of surface temperature change (1999) J. Geophys. Res., 104, pp. 30,997-31,022; Hansen, J., Ruedy, R., Lacis, A., Sato, M., Nazarenko, L., Tausnev, N., Tegen, I., Koch, D., Climate modeling in the global warming debate (2000) Climate Modeling: Past, Present and Future, , edited by D. Randall, Acad. Press, San D